		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>koitsu</b> [ Sat Mar 14, 2015 8:27 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: If MMC5 can't save the game, what mapper alike it can?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Part of your confusion probably stems from terminology (from what I can tell), and that's not your fault.<br /><br />What you are essentially wanting is &quot;battery-backed RAM&quot;.  Most cartridges implement the RAM part using SRAM (static RAM).  But colloquially people for a very long time have used the term &quot;SRAM&quot; to mean &quot;Save RAM&quot; (i.e. &quot;battery-backed RAM&quot;).  Welcome to why I hate acronyms and wish people would just say what they mean.  :-)<br /><br />But then further complication is added: throughout the Wiki (and some other documents) the term &quot;PRG-RAM&quot; is used to refer to &quot;RAM that's on the cartridge&quot; (usually wired to $6000-7FFF).  Whether or not that RAM is battery-backed or not depends on -- you guessed it -- if there's battery on the cart (historically a CR2032), powering the RAM even when the system is shut off.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
